219
00:17:46,256 --> 00:17:54,246
With that, there comes this sort of energy.

220
00:17:54,631 --> 00:18:00,317
Once you've got that conviction, once you've got that confidence, then you empower it.

221
00:18:00,337 --> 00:18:02,101
You put your energy into what you want to do.

222
00:18:03,021 --> 00:18:06,946
And that supports your concentration, which is the third one.

223
00:18:06,967 --> 00:18:09,851
So it supports your steadiness of attention.

224
00:18:12,314 --> 00:18:13,855
And then there's the mindfulness, of course.

225
00:18:14,036 --> 00:18:15,198
Just being mindful.

226
00:18:16,338 --> 00:18:17,621
Being aware of what we're doing.

227
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:19,423
It's as simple as that, basically.

228
00:18:19,943 --> 00:18:22,567
Being aware of what we're doing.

229
00:18:22,586 --> 00:18:24,569
And that includes the ethical level, you see.

230
00:18:25,376 --> 00:18:32,644
It's no good being aware of, you know, killing somebody or stabbing somebody to death.

231
00:18:32,845 --> 00:18:34,027
I mean, that's not...

232
00:18:34,047 --> 00:18:38,971
I mean, you are aware, but it isn't quite the right awareness which is going to get us liberated.

233
00:18:39,692 --> 00:18:45,338
So there's always underlying all these things, this sort of basic ethic about no harm.

234
00:18:45,358 --> 00:18:46,680
Yeah, that's your fundamental one.

235
00:18:47,260 --> 00:18:47,801
No harm.

236
00:18:50,545 --> 00:18:53,147
Sometimes you can't do by harm.

237
00:18:53,167 --> 00:18:55,349
You know, if you're a farmer, for instance, you can't

238
00:18:55,499 --> 00:18:58,803
So you have to accept there's certain limitations to them.

239
00:18:59,544 --> 00:19:01,807
But at least you don't do it with cruelty in the heart.

240
00:19:01,826 --> 00:19:04,630
That's the difference.

241
00:19:04,650 --> 00:19:07,113
So that concentration and energy go together.

242
00:19:07,133 --> 00:19:13,119
And then there's the wisdom, which is here, just a way of looking at things.

243
00:19:14,142 --> 00:19:18,586
Basically, remember, that's always referring back to these three characteristics of existence.

244
00:19:19,376 --> 00:19:22,240
just to be constantly reminding ourselves.

245
00:19:22,900 --> 00:19:27,505
It doesn't have to become obsessional, but just noticing that things come to an end.

246
00:19:28,746 --> 00:19:37,334
Every time we fall into this wrong relationship of identifying, it's me, it's mine, mine, mine, you get into some sort of unsatisfaction.

247
00:19:38,075 --> 00:19:41,739
And this sense of not-self, you can see it from the point of view of control.

248
00:19:42,459 --> 00:19:44,201
So remember, our control is minimal.

249
00:19:45,521 --> 00:19:48,404
I mean, when you're driving a car...

250
00:19:49,599 --> 00:19:58,490
there are times when you are locked into the driving and you have the impression, you have the feeling that you are in control of the car.

251
00:20:00,111 --> 00:20:03,515
And of course you are in terms of where it's going and all that.

252
00:20:03,535 --> 00:20:06,377
But as you know, the car can suddenly stop for no reason.

253
00:20:08,660 --> 00:20:09,101
And that's it.

254
00:20:09,121 --> 00:20:11,423
Then you realise you aren't in control.

255
00:20:12,163 --> 00:20:16,008
You are not in control of the car in that absolute sense.

256
00:20:16,028 --> 00:20:16,989
So it's the same with the body.

257
00:20:17,210 --> 00:20:19,471
We can wave our arms about and do...

258
00:20:19,772 --> 00:20:31,025
Speak and all that sort of stuff, but ultimately the body itself is not under our direct control So, you know the question is if it's not under this is the question that would ask if it's not under your control How can it be you?

259
00:20:32,266 --> 00:20:46,961
One of the definitions of me is that I am the center of control And the other one is through your meditation to begin to objectify things to see everything as an object Perceiver can't be the perceived

260
00:20:47,633 --> 00:20:51,817
And this takes you right back to that primal state of being the observer.

261
00:20:52,257 --> 00:20:58,864
Now that sense of self is not the sense of self that you get when you're proud or when you're embarrassed.

262
00:20:58,884 --> 00:20:59,904
That's something else.

263
00:21:00,545 --> 00:21:04,449
But that cool sort of sense of the observer within yourself.

264
00:21:04,469 --> 00:21:07,652
Remember, that's the first object you make.

265
00:21:08,893 --> 00:21:15,700
And that's the image on that screen of consciousness which draws you into the world of the mind.

266
00:21:16,455 --> 00:21:26,208
So when you come out and you're seeing, you're seeing images up here and you're feeling your knee down there and your heart's exploding with wonderful joy.

267
00:21:26,888 --> 00:21:31,153
All that, you see, remember, because you're the observer, you stepped out of it.

268
00:21:31,513 --> 00:21:33,215
You stepped out of it, you become an observer.

269
00:21:34,377 --> 00:21:36,019
So that's a magical moment, that is.

270
00:21:37,821 --> 00:21:40,164
And it's making that more and more clear to ourselves.

271
00:21:41,066 --> 00:21:43,729
That takes us back into this observer, the feeler.

272
00:21:44,349 --> 00:21:46,653
So, and then of course you can explore that.

273
00:21:49,457 --> 00:21:52,381
There must be something there that knows, eh?

274
00:21:52,401 --> 00:21:52,701
Correct?

275
00:21:53,722 --> 00:21:54,624
Note vigorously please.

276
00:21:57,167 --> 00:21:58,910
Oh God, I'm falling asleep.

277
00:21:59,832 --> 00:22:03,517
Then to do with that is the seven factors of enlightenment.

278
00:22:04,557 --> 00:22:07,201
So mindfulness of course.

279
00:22:07,789 --> 00:22:09,352
We've got the energy, you see.

280
00:22:09,832 --> 00:22:11,733
We've got the concentration.

281
00:22:11,854 --> 00:22:12,575
That's there, you see.

282
00:22:13,275 --> 00:22:16,479
We've got this, it's badly translated as joy, right?

283
00:22:16,499 --> 00:22:17,980
The best translation is interest.

284
00:22:18,079 --> 00:22:20,702
It's a real, it's an interest.

285
00:22:20,762 --> 00:22:22,724
It's a driving curiosity.

286
00:22:22,964 --> 00:22:24,026
We'll come to that later.

287
00:22:25,528 --> 00:22:29,652
You've got to be really interested in what you're investigating.

288
00:22:29,672 --> 00:22:31,272
And that's the joy of the practice, yeah?

289
00:22:32,013 --> 00:22:35,096
Tranquility, calmness.

290
00:22:35,785 --> 00:22:37,707
And then there's that sense of investigation.

291
00:22:38,729 --> 00:22:40,289
So that's the question mark in the mind.

292
00:22:40,329 --> 00:22:43,374
If the question mark's not there in your mind, that's not vipassana.

293
00:22:43,673 --> 00:22:46,017
You're doing some concentration exercise or whatever.

294
00:22:46,217 --> 00:22:48,380
So there has to be that sense of curiosity.

295
00:22:50,362 --> 00:22:50,462
Yeah?

296
00:22:50,482 --> 00:23:02,636
And finally, this quality of equanimity, which some write... Well, Jnana Ponica, the German monk, wrote the...

297
00:23:03,730 --> 00:23:05,090
The Heart of Buddhist Meditation.

298
00:23:05,672 --> 00:23:07,272
Still an absolute classic.

299
00:23:07,313 --> 00:23:08,394
Always worth a read.

300
00:23:08,994 --> 00:23:16,000
So he points out, he thinks that, or he says, in so many words, that equanimity is the greatest of all virtues.

301
00:23:16,402 --> 00:23:17,603
Keeps the balance, you see.

302
00:23:17,623 --> 00:23:23,909
Keeps us balanced.

303
00:23:23,929 --> 00:23:26,351
In these seven factors, you don't get love.

304
00:23:26,711 --> 00:23:27,612
You don't get compassion.

305
00:23:28,573 --> 00:23:30,375
It's interesting, isn't it?

306
00:23:30,394 --> 00:23:30,835
Yeah, you see.

307
00:23:31,792 --> 00:23:33,936
the presumption is that it's always there.

308
00:23:33,957 --> 00:23:38,244
I mean, you wouldn't be doing it were it not that you had a sense of care for yourself.

309
00:23:40,848 --> 00:23:43,413
And a sense of understanding that it has an outward flow.

310
00:23:44,496 --> 00:23:49,605
You know, that when... As you purify the heart, remember that part of the meditation is purifying the heart.

311
00:23:50,748 --> 00:23:52,671
When you're allowing these...

312
00:23:53,291 --> 00:24:15,502
uh fight when you're allowing the um hindrances to come up uh you know the greed the hatred all that sort of stuff when you're allowing that to come up you see as mental states that's that's a purification that is it's just blowing out so that's the effort of purification and it's there it just within the practice there's your compassion towards yourself it doesn't have to be stated

313
00:24:19,836 --> 00:24:22,398
And then there's the, so you've got those seven, yeah?

314
00:24:22,479 --> 00:24:33,608
Mindfulness, the sense of investigation, the energy, the commitment, that sense of joy, the tranquility, the concentration, equanimity.

315
00:24:33,869 --> 00:24:40,394
Now, how can you establish these when the mind is in a complete furore?

316
00:24:40,476 --> 00:24:43,939
You know, when it's going berserk or when you're actually falling asleep.

317
00:24:44,338 --> 00:24:45,920
Where are the seven factors then, you see?

318
00:24:47,142 --> 00:24:48,762
So this is what we have to understand that.

319
00:24:49,029 --> 00:24:51,833
In the awareness itself, you get those seven factors.

320
00:24:51,932 --> 00:24:58,079
So you've got your five khandhas, you see, and normally speaking, we're locked into it and getting all confused by it.

321
00:24:58,500 --> 00:24:59,961
So in our meditation, we come out.

322
00:25:00,603 --> 00:25:02,244
So this is the inner I, yeah?

323
00:25:02,644 --> 00:25:03,986
And you've got the five khandhas here.

324
00:25:06,750 --> 00:25:09,873
All those faculties come back into the awareness.

325
00:25:09,992 --> 00:25:12,256
The awareness has its equanimity.

326
00:25:12,276 --> 00:25:13,457
The awareness is calm.

327
00:25:13,477 --> 00:25:17,181
The awareness has that sense of question, you see?

328
00:25:18,190 --> 00:25:24,056
You're drawing yourself out to this point of observation.

329
00:25:24,215 --> 00:25:29,041
When you actually begin, you might feel them as something that you can experience within the body.

330
00:25:29,162 --> 00:25:31,364
Tranquility, calmness.

331
00:25:31,384 --> 00:25:37,851
But don't think that because now you don't feel calm, the quality of tranquility isn't there.

332
00:25:38,731 --> 00:25:40,814
It's there within the awareness.

333
00:25:41,094 --> 00:25:44,518
So that's always the effort to pull ourselves out and observe, you see.

334
00:25:49,173 --> 00:25:51,796
And then finally there's the Noble Eightfold Path.

335
00:25:54,018 --> 00:25:56,019
So this is an outward flow.

336
00:25:56,359 --> 00:26:01,326
So from right understanding you get a right intention.

337
00:26:01,346 --> 00:26:03,188
I always think the better word is attitude.

338
00:26:03,708 --> 00:26:04,489
Right attitude.

339
00:26:05,190 --> 00:26:08,032
And an attitude is a way of relating.

340
00:26:09,253 --> 00:26:10,134
A way of relating.

341
00:26:10,654 --> 00:26:14,980
Now this right understanding is translating itself into an ethic.

342
00:26:16,340 --> 00:26:17,221
And then from that

343
00:26:17,522 --> 00:26:21,868
you get the right speech, right action and right livelihood.

344
00:26:21,909 --> 00:26:26,434
It's interesting that he should make a big thing of livelihood because you could put it all in action.

345
00:26:27,836 --> 00:26:33,904
The action is normally described as the moral laws.

346
00:26:35,346 --> 00:26:41,134
Normally it's negative what you shouldn't do, not kill and all that, but you can also add in there what we ought to be doing.

347
00:26:42,836 --> 00:26:44,778
But livelihood, remember, is...

348
00:26:45,214 --> 00:26:46,316
It's very conditioning.

349
00:26:46,416 --> 00:26:56,809
I mean, what we do for a great deal of our lives, for eight hours a day, has to have an effect on our characters and on the way we relate to the world.

350
00:26:58,211 --> 00:27:03,278
I mean, just compare a nurse to a policeman, or a soldier.

351
00:27:04,559 --> 00:27:06,321
Now, there are virtues in being a soldier.

352
00:27:06,722 --> 00:27:10,227
We tend to be, liberals tend to be negative about soldiering.

353
00:27:11,759 --> 00:27:17,548
But soldiering has its qualities of courage and all that sort of stuff.

354
00:27:17,568 --> 00:27:21,474
St. George, our patron saint.

355
00:27:21,494 --> 00:27:29,188
So, right livelihood is put there, recognising that it is a real conditioning factor in our lives.

356
00:27:31,351 --> 00:27:38,542
And then, at the end of that, you've got the energy, the commitment, the mindfulness, and finally the concentration.

357
00:27:41,594 --> 00:27:46,601
normally you get it divided as sila, samadhi and panya.

358
00:27:46,661 --> 00:27:49,265
So sila is your morality.

359
00:27:50,145 --> 00:27:55,192
Samadhi is your concentration, ability for your, just the steadiness of attention.

360
00:27:55,413 --> 00:27:58,537
We're not talking about big heavy jhanas here.

361
00:27:58,557 --> 00:28:07,369
And the mindfulness is your awareness, which has included in it this sense of grasping, this intuitive faculty.

362
00:28:08,991 --> 00:28:09,913
Now you can see how

363
00:28:10,078 --> 00:28:18,332
this revolves around itself because if we develop a right attitude, that's got to feed back into our understanding.

364
00:28:20,795 --> 00:28:38,803
So the more that we develop a right attitude, shall we say, to all these refugees, see, some people feel very negative about them, but if they develop a right attitude, then you get the wisdom, which is, of course, that we're all human beings and we're all

365
00:28:39,307 --> 00:28:40,909
We're all suffering to one level or another.

366
00:28:42,151 --> 00:28:42,672
Things like that.

367
00:28:43,333 --> 00:28:51,123
So with that right attitude, developing right attitude has an effect on the way that we understand life.

368
00:28:52,125 --> 00:29:05,482
And just being, just the way we speak, you know, taking, being careful about what we say, the four things, you know, kindly speech, truthful speech, speech at the right time,

369
00:29:08,332 --> 00:29:09,272
suitable time.

370
00:29:09,834 --> 00:29:15,481
So, you know, practicing that has an effect on our understanding about relationship, about how we relate to each other.

371
00:29:17,565 --> 00:29:19,346
So that's the Noble Eightfold Path.

372
00:29:19,367 --> 00:29:23,553
So I just want to go back now to the four bases of magical power.

373
00:29:27,077 --> 00:29:28,299
Where's my magical powers?

374
00:29:28,500 --> 00:29:28,921
Here we are.

375
00:29:30,383 --> 00:29:38,253
So there are five magical powers, none of which very few people believe in in our society.

376
00:29:38,673 --> 00:29:40,675
They just think it's a bit of a joke, really.

377
00:29:43,099 --> 00:29:50,951
So the Buddha says that somebody who practices these wields manifold supranormal powers.

378
00:29:52,673 --> 00:29:57,140
Having been one, he becomes many, and having been many, he becomes one.

379
00:29:57,160 --> 00:29:57,922
By location.

380
00:29:58,561 --> 00:30:05,692
He can walk through walls and ramparts and mountains, walk over water, sitting cross-legged, flies through the air like a winged bird.

381
00:30:06,971 --> 00:30:13,939
Now how many of you are going to believe that?

382
00:30:16,421 --> 00:30:19,723
You see, we are deeply sceptical of these things.

383
00:30:20,325 --> 00:30:21,224
Deeply sceptical.

384
00:30:23,768 --> 00:30:25,710
Remind me of, oh dear, I've forgotten her name.

385
00:30:26,589 --> 00:30:26,770
Deepamar.

386
00:30:27,070 --> 00:30:28,372
Yes, Deepamar, thank you.

387
00:30:28,771 --> 00:30:29,833
Thank you, Trevor.

388
00:30:29,853 --> 00:30:34,718
If you read the book on Deepamar, who was this Indian lady, she was able to do this.

389
00:30:36,789 --> 00:30:39,311
I'll give you a few examples afterwards.

390
00:30:39,332 --> 00:30:45,557
Then there's the divine ear to see things which are really beyond the normal range of things.

391
00:30:46,659 --> 00:30:49,740
Then there's the awareness of other beings, other individuals.

392
00:30:52,703 --> 00:30:54,085
Sorry, that's a bad translation.

393
00:30:54,384 --> 00:30:56,247
To be able to read other people's minds.

394
00:30:57,667 --> 00:31:00,431
Have I told you the story of this Jungian psychotherapist?

395
00:31:02,251 --> 00:31:03,773
You haven't heard my story, right?

396
00:31:04,193 --> 00:31:05,295
Well, I was in the Isle of Man.

397
00:31:05,781 --> 00:31:21,984
And we used to go to, when I went over there, a couple of times we were taken, I went over with Pam and, I can't remember, what was the name of the other elderly lady?

398
00:31:22,005 --> 00:31:25,229
We used to go over to listen to talks given by this Jungian.

399
00:31:25,710 --> 00:31:27,432
Paddy and Pam, wasn't it?

400
00:31:27,451 --> 00:31:28,453
Yeah, that's it, Paddy.

401
00:31:29,075 --> 00:31:32,920
So she took me over to listen to the talks given by this Jungian therapist.

402
00:31:33,523 --> 00:31:37,409
He was already retired.

403
00:31:38,230 --> 00:31:51,568
But after he'd given this talk, he said to me that he'd been to Burma because he'd become very interested in Buddhism, in the teaching of Buddhism.

404
00:31:52,109 --> 00:31:56,936
And when he got to Rangoon, he asked, where should he go to really learn about Buddhism?

405
00:31:57,217 --> 00:32:02,163
They said, well, you should go to the teaching monasteries up in Mandalay, the big university monasteries.

406
00:32:03,612 --> 00:32:07,297
So he was given an interpreter.

407
00:32:07,317 --> 00:32:11,000
And he went up to talk to this very elderly monk.

408
00:32:11,020 --> 00:32:14,345
And he said he just sat in a chair surrounded by books.

409
00:32:16,147 --> 00:32:17,308
This elderly monk.

410
00:32:17,328 --> 00:32:19,952
And they discussed the Dharma for two hours.

411
00:32:20,973 --> 00:32:21,473
Thereabouts.

412
00:32:22,836 --> 00:32:26,621
And it was only when he was leaving that he realised he hadn't used the interpreter.

413
00:32:28,363 --> 00:32:31,527
And there was still that sense of shock on his face when he told me.

414
00:32:33,463 --> 00:32:36,548
Figure that out.

415
00:32:36,567 --> 00:32:40,972
I won't say any more.

416
00:32:41,093 --> 00:32:42,295
Recollect past lives.

417
00:32:42,575 --> 00:32:44,597
People do recollect past lives.

418
00:32:45,578 --> 00:32:46,480
Even people who come here.

419
00:32:47,601 --> 00:32:54,730
A past life recollection, the telltale is that when that memory comes up, you are a different person.

420
00:32:59,619 --> 00:33:07,606
It's not as though you have a conversation, well, you know, I was Napoleon in my past life.

421
00:33:08,127 --> 00:33:10,430
And the person you're talking to said, so was I.

422
00:33:14,614 --> 00:33:22,480
There's a lot of research done by Stevenson, so you can read about it.

423
00:33:24,342 --> 00:33:27,265
And I've got a video there about this little American boy.

424
00:33:27,582 --> 00:33:56,491
has a tremendous past life experience recall as a as a pilot downed in the pacific during the japanese uh american japanese war there second world war and uh you know he goes to see the the the the sister of this particular pilot and they have a conversation the sister says he knows things about the family that only we know this guy lives somewhere else um you also get

425
00:33:56,876 --> 00:34:01,483
extraordinary powers which are very hard to explain.

426
00:34:02,525 --> 00:34:18,789
There was a programme, I think, on this young girl, about 10 or 12 or something, and she's composed an opera which is being performed in Austria, and she's there directing the orchestra, telling the conductor what to do and what not to do.

427
00:34:19,449 --> 00:34:20,351
Somebody told me about it.

428
00:34:20,411 --> 00:34:22,213
I saw a little clip about her.

429
00:34:22,235 --> 00:34:23,255
I said, how do you explain that?

430
00:34:25,311 --> 00:34:26,873
I shall leave that to the scientists.

431
00:34:28,797 --> 00:34:30,480
So, past lives.

432
00:34:31,161 --> 00:34:31,902
Divine eye.

433
00:34:32,842 --> 00:34:38,552
You can see things that...

434
00:34:38,811 --> 00:34:42,438
The divine eye is often also seeing a person as they really are.

435
00:34:44,740 --> 00:34:49,969
Remember, you sometimes get in Buddhism, you hear people saying when two people meet, there are six people there.

436
00:34:50,556 --> 00:34:58,045
There's you as I see you, and there's you as you see you, and there's you as you really are.

437
00:34:58,065 --> 00:34:59,106
And the same applies to me.

438
00:35:00,027 --> 00:35:02,990
So how we communicate is a wonder.

439
00:35:04,873 --> 00:35:07,835
And the final one is the spiritual one.

440
00:35:08,496 --> 00:35:13,882
The fact that all the mental defilements are completely destroyed.

441
00:35:15,463 --> 00:35:18,807
And then one is known to be released from suffering.

442
00:35:21,606 --> 00:35:28,894
Now, the reason I've pulled this up is that that's, the Buddha talks, I mean, that's in the scriptures, all this is in the scriptures.

443
00:35:28,914 --> 00:35:35,041
But when we look at the actual faculties, they are, of course, something we have to take into daily life.

444
00:35:35,541 --> 00:35:43,690
And being the new year, these give us some idea of those qualities we need to really develop.

445
00:35:44,871 --> 00:35:49,976
I believe in Thailand, these, you know, they'll talk about the Yiddish, these powers.

446
00:35:50,632 --> 00:35:56,601
Just in ordinary discourse, like, you know, if you want somebody to do better, they'll say, well, you know, practice these iddys.

447
00:35:57,483 --> 00:36:05,637
So the first one is chanda, which translates as sort of desire, but it's a very, very strong desire.

448
00:36:07,940 --> 00:36:14,090
Can you think of some time in your life when you really, really, really wanted something?

449
00:36:16,635 --> 00:36:20,681
That's the sort of desire you need to become liberated.

450
00:36:22,144 --> 00:36:24,728
So you really, really want it.

451
00:36:25,710 --> 00:36:33,041
And then once you've... What that does is empower you to put tremendous energy behind that desire for success.

452
00:36:33,923 --> 00:36:36,748
When we say success here, you've got to be careful.

453
00:36:36,807 --> 00:36:40,173
You're aiming at something which you think is worthwhile in your life.

454
00:36:42,878 --> 00:36:42,998
Right?

455
00:36:44,597 --> 00:36:48,782
Now, in the meditation, of course, we don't aim to get nibbana.

456
00:36:48,822 --> 00:36:52,907
What we aim is purity of heart and insight into the faculties.

457
00:36:53,447 --> 00:36:54,628
The rest happens of itself.

458
00:36:55,469 --> 00:36:58,373
But without that real strong commitment, you see.

459
00:37:01,996 --> 00:37:05,780
And the third one is a total application of the mind.

460
00:37:05,940 --> 00:37:08,344
Here, citta means both mind and heart.

461
00:37:08,384 --> 00:37:10,346
It's not just thinking, for heaven's sake.

462
00:37:10,365 --> 00:37:13,710
It's just the whole being is devoted to what you're doing.

463
00:37:15,512 --> 00:37:19,217
And to maintain a sense of discrimination.

464
00:37:19,938 --> 00:37:23,882
To maintain always that sense of questioning what you're doing.

465
00:37:23,902 --> 00:37:26,264
There's always that reflection about what we're doing.

466
00:37:26,885 --> 00:37:29,106
So if you think of those four things now.

467
00:37:29,606 --> 00:37:31,168
So you really want something.

468
00:37:32,530 --> 00:37:34,693
Yeah, ice cream.

469
00:37:35,112 --> 00:37:36,795
You really want something.

470
00:37:36,815 --> 00:37:38,777
And then you put your energy behind it.

471
00:37:39,336 --> 00:37:39,978
Real energy.

472
00:37:40,157 --> 00:37:40,878
Commitment.

473
00:37:41,668 --> 00:37:42,530
No holes barred.

474
00:37:43,771 --> 00:37:49,239
And with that energy, you're putting the whole of your mental powers into what you're doing.

475
00:37:51,222 --> 00:37:58,612
But you maintain always that sense of self-examination, self-reflection, reflecting what you're doing.

476
00:37:58,632 --> 00:38:07,525
Now, when we, according to the Buddha, when we exercise those four things, you will achieve something of what you've aimed out to do.

477
00:38:09,429 --> 00:38:10,090
So that's your...

478
00:38:10,525 --> 00:38:17,175
Those are your ides, those are your power, your four bases of power.

479
00:38:17,255 --> 00:38:20,480
Sometimes it's just put as the four bases of power.

480
00:38:21,201 --> 00:38:23,625
So power is what you can achieve.

481
00:38:24,485 --> 00:38:27,130
Influence is what you can get other people to do for you.

482
00:38:27,771 --> 00:38:30,255
But power is what you can achieve.

483
00:38:30,590 --> 00:39:00,208
when you for instance um want to do something if you if you get confused between the edge of your power and the edges of influence then that's where your frustration that's where your frustration arises so you're not reflecting and saying well i can't do that or i can do it see a lot of that is experimentation as to what you can do what you can't do so take these people who are very much involved in in compassionate work you know uh

